  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2714571391?book_show_action=true">Feb 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nancy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nancy" href="/user/show/3628674-nancy">Nancy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/32077564-an-innocent-client">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3628674-nancy?shelf=2019-read">2019-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2714571391" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13991704800480487">Interesting storyline, nice short chapters, characters were written quite well. Three stars is suppose to mean &quot;I Liked It&quot; and I did, I just did not REALLY Like it. Wasn&apos;t left with a yearning to know what was going to happen next when I took a break from reading. The strongest emotion I got from the book was the complete dislike, and great desire to see justice done to TBI Special Agent Phillip Landers. Pratt wrote him as such a despicable individual you just hoped he also wrote a fitting endi</span>
  <span id="freeText13991704800480487" style="display:none">Interesting storyline, nice short chapters, characters were written quite well. Three stars is suppose to mean "I Liked It" and I did, I just did not REALLY Like it. Wasn't left with a yearning to know what was going to happen next when I took a break from reading. The strongest emotion I got from the book was the complete dislike, and great desire to see justice done to TBI Special Agent Phillip Landers. Pratt wrote him as such a despicable individual you just hoped he also wrote a fitting ending for him - and he did. Other characters were interesting and some entertaining. The main character, Joe Dillard, started out well but got to be a bit whining and unkind to those who loved him as the stresses in his life mounted. <br /><br />I listened to this book on my tablet while reading it. Although Scott Pratt has lived in Tennessee since he was 13 he did not advise the narrator that Tennesseans do not have a southern twang like the one he gave Erlene Barlowe or several others. That's a good ole Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana drawl there and not close to anyone I've ever met in TN. Other than that, the narrator did a fine job with the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13991704800480487" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


